Program name: Master of Science in Education in Adolescence Education: Mathematics + Students with Disabilities Certification
Requirements: Completed online application, including: Application fee. Official transcripts from all accredited colleges or universities attended. Two letters of recommendation (one must be from a faculty member and one must be from a supervisor). A statement of objectives that explains how the program relates to the applicant’s personal and professional goals. A current resume. Meet the requirements listed under Option I, II, or III below. OPTION I - To be unconditionally accepted into the program, applicants must have a minimum cumulative GPA of 3.0 on a 4.0 scale. OPTION II - Applicants with a minimum cumulative GPA of 2.75 - 2.99 on a 4.0 scale will be considered for admission based on a minimum score on the Graduate Record Examination (GRE): Verbal 147; Quantitative 147; Analytical Writing 3.0. OPTION III - Applicants with a minimum cumulative GPA of 2.5 - 2.74 on a 4.0 scale will be considered for admission based on a minimum score on the Graduate Record Examination (GRE): Verbal 150; Quantitative 150; Analytical Writing 3.5. Note: Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the GRE requirement is currently being waived. In addition, all applicants must have successfully completed: A major in Mathematics with a minimum of 30 credit hours in mathematics coursework, 12 of which must be at the 300-level or above. The coursework should include courses in calculus, linear algebra, geometry, abstract algebra, statistics/probability, and the history of mathematics.
